Question: I'm in salary band C and my line manager asked me to work several
  hours last Saturday because of a publication deadline. If I take
  payment instead of compensatory leave, how is the amount calculated?
Example answer: For members of staff with a basic salary up to step 59 of salary band
  E, overtime worked on Saturdays, Sundays and public holidays is
  compensated at two hours for each hour of overtime worked. Where
  compensatory leave for overtime cannot be granted, the member of
  staff may instead be granted overtime payment in lieu of leave, and
  the standard hourly rate for such payment is 0.6% of the basic
  monthly salary for the month in which the overtime was worked. (ECB
  Conditions of Employment, page 13; ECB Staff Rules, pages 89–90)
Predicted answer: To calculate the payment for overtime when you choose payment in lieu
  of compensatory leave: - Find your basic monthly salary for the
  relevant month (Band C). - Compute the standard hourly rate as 0.6%
  of that monthly salary: hourly rate = 0.006 × (basic monthly
  salary). - Multiply by the number of overtime hours worked on the
  Saturday: gross payment = (number of hours) × (0.006 × basic monthly
  salary). - Apply the overtime tax rate for that month to this
  amount; this is the only deduction mentioned for these payments. No
  other deductions apply. - The net amount is paid with your monthly
  salary (i.e., included in your regular paycheck for that month).
  Example: If basic monthly salary = EUR 3,000 and you worked 5
  overtime hours, gross = 5 × (0.006 × 3,000) = EUR 90. After tax at
  the applicable rate, you receive the net amount with your salary.
